johnsos@holmes.ece.orst.edu (scott johnson) writes:

>In article <dbarber.769068373@crash.cts.com>,
>David C. Barber <dbarber@crash.cts.com> wrote:
>>Does RSA only operate properly when you can create a number that is
>>the product of 2 primes?
>>

>RSA operates properly for any n if you can find d and e, such that 
>de mod phi(n)=1.  The product of two primes is used because

>>If so, does it matter if one of the primes is very small (e.g. 2)?
> 
>The algorithm will work if 2 is one of the prime factors.

>>
>>If the above is true, can it be used to determine if a large number is
>>a prime by doubling said large number (i.e. multiply by prime value 2)
>>and then run an RSA encrypt/decrypt cycle to prove that a valid pair
>>of primes was used?

>You could possibly prove a number is NOT prime in this manner, by assuming it is
>prime, calculating phi(n) accordingly, and if RSA fails, you know your phi(n) is 
>wrong.  However, a correct result does not imply primality--if your estimate of
>phi(n) is a multiple of the correct phi(n), then  RSA will work, but the factor in
>question is not prime.  I'll leave the rest to a more experienced number theorist.

An old primality test is as follows: To test primality of $n$, calculate
$b=a^n \mod n$ for several values of $a$.  If each $b$ equals its $a$, then
you may have a prime.  This is based on a (Euler's?) theorem that states
that $a^{\phi(n)} \mod n =1$.  (This is the basis of RSA).

